'''Prisoner X''' is a [[placeholder name]] used by [[Journalist|reporters]] for some prisoners in Israel:<ref name=upi>{{Cite web | author = [[United Press International]] | title = Israel's Prisoner X isn't the first | accessdate = 8 October 2015 | date = 19 February 2013 | url = http://www.upi.com/Top_News/Special/2013/02/19/Israels-Prisoner-X-isnt-the-first/UPI-55831361313280/ | publisher = upi.com }}</ref> The designation is used "to identify Israeli inmates who “work in institutions linked to security whose activities are shrouded in secrecy."<ref name=RT>{{cite news|url=https://www.rt.com/news/israel-secret-prisoner-x-845/|title=Prisoner X2: Second Israeli agent secretly locked away on ‘sensational’ charges |date=12 July 2013 |publisher=RT.com|accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>
* [[Death of Ben Zygier|Ben Zygier]] was held in [[Ayalon Prison]] in [[Israel]] until his death there in 2010. * [[Lavon Affair|Avri Elad]] (d 1993) was held in Ayalon Prison. * [[Marcus Klingberg]] was held from 1983 to 2003 in Israel * Mordechai Kedar, recruited by Israeli Military Intelligence in 1956<ref name=upi/> * "[[Prisoner X2]]" - an unidentified prisoner who has been held in Ayalon Prison "for many years" ({{As of|2013|7|lc=y}})<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-23187419|author=Knell, Yolande |title=Israel 'secretly holds second Prisoner X' in jail|date=12 July 2013 |publisher=BBC News|accessdate=8 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=RT/>
