{{Use Indian English|date=October 2013}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}
{{Dravidian}}
'''South Indian culture''' refers to the culture of the [[South India]]n states of [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[Karnataka]], [[Kerala]], [[Tamil Nadu]], and [[Telangana]]. South Indian culture though with its visible differences forms an important part of the Indian culture. The South Indian Culture is essentially the celebration of the eternal [[universe]] through the celebration of the [[beauty]] of the body and [[mother]]hood.<ref name= "beck">Beck, Brenda. 1976. "The Symbolic Merger of Body, Space, and Cosmos in Hindu Tamil Nadu." Contributions to Indian Sociology 10(2): 213-43.</ref><ref name= "Bharata">Bharata (1967). The Natyashastra [Dramaturgy], 2 vols., 2nd. ed. Trans. by Manomohan Ghosh. Calcutta: Manisha Granthalaya.</ref><ref name= "Dehejia">Dehejia, Vidya, Richard H. Davis, R. Nagaswamy, Karen Pechilis Prentiss (2002) The Sensuous and the Sacred: Chola Bronzes from South India. {{ISBN|0-295-98284-5}}</ref><ref name= "Kallarasa">Kallarasa Virachita Janavasya Ed: G.G. Manjunathan. Kannada Adhyayana Samsthe, University of Mysore, Mysore 1974</ref><ref name= "Wadley">Wadley, Susan, ed. 1980. The Powers of Tamil Women. Syracuse: Syracuse U. Press.</ref> It is exemplified through its [[dance]], [[clothing]], and [[sculptures]].<ref name="beck"/><ref name="Bharata"/><ref name="Dehejia"/><ref name="Kallarasa"/><ref name="Wadley"/>

== Traditional clothing ==
South Indian women traditionally wear the saree while the men wear a type of [[sarong]], which could be either a white ''[[dhoti]]'' or a colourful ''[[lungi]]'' with typical [[batik]] patterns. The saree, being an unstitched [[Draped garment|drape]], enhances the shape of the wearer while only partially covering the midriff. In Indian philosophy, the navel of the Supreme Being is considered as the source of life and creativity.<ref name="beck"/><ref name="Bharata"/><ref name="Dehejia"/><ref name="Wadley"/> Hence by tradition, the stomach and the navel is to be left unconcealed, though the philosophy behind the costume has largely been forgotten.<ref name="beck"/><ref name="Bharata"/><ref name="Dehejia"/><ref name="Kallarasa"/><ref name="Wadley"/> This makes the realization of ''sharira-mandala'', where in ''Angikam bhuvanam yasya'' (the body is your world) unites with the ''shaarira-mandala'' (the whole universe), as expressed in the [[Natyashastra]].<ref name="beck"/><ref name="Bharata"/><ref name="Dehejia"/><ref name="Kallarasa"/><ref name="Wadley"/> These principles of the sari, also hold for other forms of drapes, like the [[lungi]] or [[mundu]] or [[dhoti|panchey]] (a white lungi with colourful silk borders in [[kannada]]), worn by men.<ref name="Boulanger">Boulanger, Chantal; (1997) Saris: An Illustrated Guide to the Indian Art of Draping, Shakti Press International, New York. {{ISBN|0-9661496-1-0}}</ref> The lungi is draped over clockwise or counterclockwise and is tied at the back or fixed just along the waistline. It's sometimes lifted to the knee and tied at the waist leisurely or just held in hand to speed up walking.

Traditionally, South Indian men do not cover their upper body. Sometimes, in a formal situation, a piece of cloth may cover the upper body. Certain temples in South India even ban men from wearing upper-body garments when inside the temple. In Andhra and parts of north Karnataka, men wear kachche panchey where it is tied at back by taking it between legs.  A similar pattern is seen in women. All over the peninsular coastal region, men wear coloured lungis and women wear saris in a manner of tying them at the back.

[[File:Araimudi.jpg|right|thumb|250px|The Araimudi (araimuti) was worn by young [[Tamil people|Tamil]] girls.]]
The [[Araimudi]] (araimuti) ({{Indic|lang=ta|indic=அரைமுடி|trans=araimūḍi}}) is a small silver metal plate, shaped like a heart or a fig leaf, formerly worn by young [[Tamil people|Tamil]] girls on their genitals.<ref>[http://www.tamildictionary.org/tamil_english.php?id=2236 Tamil to English Dictionary "Meaning of iravirekku" (Meaning of இராவிரேக்கு)]</ref><ref>[http://tamil.indianlanguages.org/dictionary/meaning.php?id=2054&lang=Tamil TAMIL TO ENGLISH DICTIONARY இராவிரேக்கு - iravirekku - &#91;irāvirēkku&#93;]</ref><ref>[http://www.tamilvu.org/slet/servlet/lexpg?pageno=118 அரசிலை  aracilai] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023060038/http://www.tamilvu.org/slet/servlet/lexpg?pageno=118 |date=23 October 2013 }}</ref> "Arai" means loin and "mudi" means cover.<ref>{{cite book|edition=|year=2007|publisher=Asiff Hussein|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1kVuAAAAMAAJ&q=arai+mudi+araimuti+girls&dq=arai+mudi+araimuti+girls&hl=en&sa=X&ei=MW-gUNeZEoqx0AGr8YCYCg&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAA|volume=VOL. I.—THE DISTRICT|author=Asiff Hussein|quote=110 The term appears to literally mean 'loin (arai) cover (mudi)' 4,1 Winslow ( 1862) gives araimuti as 'a small plate of metal worn by little girls over the private parts'. Dubois (1906) who observed that the private parts of the children of the|accessdate=11 November 2012|location=MADRAS : PRINTED BY E. KEYS, AT THE GOVERNMENT PRESS|title=Sarandib: an ethnological study of the Muslims of Sri Lanka|page=267|isbn=9559726226|editor=}}Original from the University of Michigan Digitized 3 Sep 2008</ref> The araimudi is also known as the "Genital shield" and an araimudi was mentioned in the "Guide to the principal exhibits in the Government Museum, Pudukkottai", by M. S. Chandrasekhar, published in 1966 as being displayed in an exhibit in the [[Government Museum, Chennai|Madras Government Museum]].<ref>{{cite book|edition=|year=1966|publisher=Printed at Super Power Press, for the Director of Stationery and Print.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SCUjAQAAMAAJ&q=araimudi&dq=araimudi&hl=en&sa=X&ei=hYuMT_fwOqPl0QHFy-zBCQ&ved=0CEQQ6AEwAw|volume=|author=Government Museum (Madras, India), M. S. Chandrasekhar|quote=Pamla malai (coral necklace), kasais, lead and glass bangles, lead rings for toes, ear and nose screws, and also the araimudi (or the " Genital shield ") worn by young female children are included.|accessdate=16 April 2012|location=|title=Guide to the principal exhibits in the Government Museum, Pudukkottai|page=93|isbn=|editor=}}Original from the University of Michigan Digitized 6 Jun 2011 Length 129 pages</ref> "A Manual of the Salem district in the presidency of Madras, Volume 1" said "The children sometimes, to the age of ten years or more, go in a state of nudity, relieved perhaps by a piece of string round the waist which sustains the "araimudi" or heart-shaped piece of silver, which calls attention to what it purports to conceal."<ref>{{cite book|edition=|year=1883|publisher=Printed by E. Keys, at the Government Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_ZEIAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA141&dq=araimudi&hl=en&sa=X&ei=hYuMT_fwOqPl0QHFy-zBCQ&ved=0CDoQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=araimudi&f=false|volume=VOL. I.—THE DISTRICT|author=|quote=The children sometimes, to the age of ten years or more, go in a state of nudity, relieved perhaps by a piece of string round the waist which sustains the "araimudi" or heart-shaped piece of silver, which calls attention to what it purports to conceal.|accessdate=16 April 2012|location=MADRAS : PRINTED BY E. KEYS, AT THE GOVERNMENT PRESS|title=A Manual of the Salem district in the presidency of Madras, Volume 1|page=141|isbn=|editor=}}Compiled by Henry Le Fanu Original from Oxford University Digitized 6 Jun 2007</ref> The "Madras district gazetteers, Volume 1, Part 1" said 'Little girls, up to the age of about 3, wear nothing but the little heart-shaped piece of silver suspended by a waist-cord (arai- mudi) " which calls attention to what it purports to conceal."'<ref>{{cite book|edition=|year=1918|publisher=Printed by the Superintendent, Govt. Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CglmG0VjScYC&q=arai+mudi+girls&dq=arai+mudi+girls&hl=en&sa=X&ei=8RigUO3MJYKR0QGAvIDwCA&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAQ|volume=VOL. I.—THE DISTRICT|author=Madras (India : State)|quote=Little girls, up to the age of about 3, wear nothing but the little heart-shaped piece of silver suspended by a waist-cord (arai- mudi) "which calls attention to what it purports to conceal." They are then promoted to a miniaturo " female " cloth|accessdate=11 November 2012|location=MADRAS : PRINTED BY E. KEYS, AT THE GOVERNMENT PRESS|title=Madras district gazetteers, Volume 1, Part 1|page=109|isbn=|editor=}}Original from the University of Michigan Digitized	14 Mar 2005 {{cite web |url=http://202.41.82.144/rawdataupload/upload/0105/094/TXT/00000127.txt |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-11-12 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121203164830/http://202.41.82.144/rawdataupload/upload/0105/094/TXT/00000127.txt |archivedate=3 December 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> "Percival's Tamil-English dictionary", edited by P. Percival defined Araimudi as "அரைமுடி arai múḍi, A small plate of gold or silver, appended to the girdle of female children, for the sake of decency".<ref>{{cite book|edition=reprint|year=1993|publisher=Asian Educational Services|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u6YdKeY6JHcC&dq=jyfacfutf.+arai+mudi%2C+A+small+plate+of+gold+or+silver%2C+appended+to+the+girdle+of+female+children%2C+for+the+saka+of+decency&q=arai+mudi#v=snippet&q=arai%20mudi&f=false|volume=|author=P. Percival|quote=அரைமுடி arai múḍi, A small plate of gold or silver, appended to the girdle of female children, for the sake of decency ;|accessdate=16 April 2012|location=|title=Percival's Tamil-English dictionary|page=14|isbn=81-206-0819-4|editor=P. Percival}}[https://books.google.com/books?id=u6YdKeY6JHcC&pg=PA14&dq=araimudi&hl=en&sa=X&ei=E5KMT6GxAuTC0AGmr63BCQ&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=araimudi&f=false 